Your earlier comment about 10 and zero actually shows up here too.

If we look at the Taylor expansion of the exponential:

e^{ix} =
1 + ix - \frac{x^2}{2!} - i\frac{x^3}{3!} + \frac{x^4}{4!} + ...

the real and imaginary parts automatically separate into cosine and sine.

So the sine and cosine waves are already hiding inside the exponential.

